<div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
	 <h4 class="header">Remarks</h4>
	<div class="text"> <i>Menodora spinescens </i>occurs in the eastern and southern Mojave Desert and adjacent western Great Basin. It presents itself as a dense, low green-stemmed and extremely spiny shrub. Although the species is widespread from the upper creosote bush zone into the lower pinyon-juniper belt, the alliance occurs in small, local areas at middle elevations. <br/>
<br/>
Stand dynamics are uncertain, but <i>M. spinescens </i>tends to occur in areas otherwise occupied by upland associations of the <i>Atriplex confertifolia </i>alliance, which suggests that <i>M. spinescens </i>is a more stable component of the vegetation in areas where <i>A. confertifolia </i>waxes and wanes as a result of natural pathogen disturbance (Thomas et al. 2004). Stands also mix with those of the <i>Artemisia tridentata, Coleogyne ramosissima, Ephedra nevadensis, </i>and <i>Grayia spinosa </i>alliances. <i>M. spinescens </i>appears sensitive to disturbance such as intensive grazing and fire, and it usually grows on shallow, rocky uplands at mid-elevations. </div>
</div>

    
	
	
