    <div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
        <h4 class="header">Regional Status</h4>
        

        <ul class="text">
        
            <li><b>Mojave Desert</b> (322Ad, Af, Ah, Aj-l, An). Stands occur in the southern and eastern sections north through Death Valley National Park (Thomas et al. 2004). Some have experienced long-term grazing (e.g., near Cima Dome). Although most stands are on rocky soils of pediments and low-gradient hills, some stands occur on upper bajadas on alluvial soil in Greenwater Valley. Stands commonly associate with low density, short stature <i>Yucca brevifolia</i> stands, and with upland ones of <i>Atriplex confertifolia.</i></li>
        
            <li><b>Mono</b> (341Dj). Stands occur at mid to lower elevations in the southern White Mountains.</li>
        
            <li><b>Southeastern Great Basin</b> (341Fb-f). Stands occur in the upper elevations of Death Valley National Park and in the adjacent Argus and Last Chance ranges. Most of the 1760 ha mapped in the Mojave Desert study (Thomas et al. 2004) occurred in this section.</li>
        
        </ul>
    </div>


    
	
<div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
	 <h4 class="header">Management Considerations</h4>
	<div class="text"> This alliance requires further study before suggesting proper management. <i>Menodora spinescens </i>may tolerate some degree of grazing because of its extremely spiny habit; however, it appears in relatively stable sites. It may be frost sensitive and potentially indicate the upper boundary of the Mojave Desert during times of fluctuating climatic conditions. Drought also could affect the presence of stands; for example, Webb et al. (2003) found that areas of the Nevada Test Site previously dominated by <i>M. spinescens </i>now have cover of other species such as <i>Larrea tridentata, </i>relating this change to series of drought years. </div>
</div>

    

    

